==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Escarp
<hw>Es*carp"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>escarpe</ets> (cf. Sp. <ets>escarpa</ets>, It. <ets>scarpa</ets>),
fr. <ets>escarper</ets> to cut steep, cut to a slope, prob. of German
origin: cf. G. <ets>scharf</ets> sharp,, E. <ets>sharp</ets>, or perh.
<ets>scrape</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>The side of the ditch
next the parapet; -- same as <altname>scarp</altname>, and opposed to
<contr>counterscarp</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Escarp</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Escarp
<hw>Es*carp"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Escarped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Escarping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To make into,
or furnish with, a steep slope, like that of a scrap.</def>
<rj><au>Carleton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Escarpment</ent>⟦br⟧
